    <title>Combined summary - BIP 100 specification</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T21:58:30.843422+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-September/010874.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin community is engaged in discussions related to the block size limit for Bitcoin. Members of the community are proposing various thresholds for initiation of a hardfork and advocating for symmetrical thresholds for increase and decrease. The deployment method is suggested to be a separate issue from blocksize proposals, and discussions on consensus forks are encouraged to take place separately. There are also technical details being discussed, including the range of the hardLimit, byte resolution, how votes are counted, and how the new hardLimit is calculated. Some members suggest replacing the static 1M block size hard limit with a floating limit that floats within the range of 1-32M. In addition, the use of a merkleblock message to send messages that only contain part of a block is suggested.The email thread includes a revision suggestion for the calculation of hardLimit based on the coinbase scriptSig votes. It is suggested that the initiation of a hardfork should be based on its acceptance by the economic majority, not just miner support. Some members are advocating for separate discussions on certain topics to ensure efficient conversation. There are debates over the 75% rule and the implication threshold, with some arguing for an 80% threshold instead of 95%. A new initial public draft of BIP 100 has been released by jgarzik on Github.The Bitcoin community is discussing the proposal for increasing or decreasing the block size limit for Bitcoin. Suggestions are made regarding the implementation of a new hardLimit for block sizes, including using a 4-byte unsigned integer instead of human-readable strings and allowing miners to vote for the status quo by indicating it in the coinbase. Additionally, there are debates about the 75% rule, whether invalid version 4 blocks should always be rejected, and whether absent votes should be considered as votes for the status quo.In a discussion on the bitcoin-dev mailing list, several updates were proposed for the block size limit, including the use of "megabyte" to exclusively mean 2^20 (1,048,576) bytes and for "Kb" to always mean 1024 bytes. Dave Scotese raised the issue of varying interpretations of the term "1M" in relation to bytes used by different people within the industry.Regarding the new hardLimit, votes were suggested to sort from lowest to highest for the last 12,000 blocks. Blocks that do not have a vote are considered a vote for the status quo. Votes are limited to +/- 20% of the current value. The raise value is defined as the vote for the 2400th highest block (20th percentile), and the lower value is defined as the vote for the 9600th highest block (80th percentile).The email chain includes a revision suggestion for the calculation of hardLimit based on the coinbase scriptSig votes. The new hardLimit will be calculated by sorting the coinbase scriptSig votes from lowest to highest and using the vote of the 2400th block. If the change in the vote of the 2400th block is less than 20%, then it will be used as the new hardLimit. Otherwise, the hardLimit will be changed either to 120% or 80% of the current hardLimit. Jeff Garzik posts a link to the initial public draft of BIP 100, emphasizing that it is a starting point for feedback and iteration rather than an endpoint. The email signer provides their technical skills and links to their website and projects.</summary>
